Pearson correlation coefficients (PCC)¶

In [2]:
def cal_pcc(x):
    # :: mean of data matrix
    mean_x = x.mean(axis=0)

    # :: center the data
    center_x = x - mean_x

    # :: standardize the data with mean of 0 and variance/s.d. of 1
    std_x = center_x / np.sqrt((center_x ** 2).sum(axis=0))

    # PCC
    return np.dot(std_x.T, std_x)

prepare data matrix¶

This section is to prepare a data matrix with smaller number of variables to speed up the calculations. It would be extremely slow to perform the analysis on relatively large data matrix. In this section, ~50 variables will be prepared. 1. Small PCCs in both groups. 2. Large PCcs in one group not in the other. 3. Large Pccs in both groups. !!!IMPORTANT: This section can be skipped if the data matrix is small or the original data matrix is intensionally analyzed using PCLRC.

PCLRC: probabilistic context likelihood of relatedness¶

In [11]:
# Creates pclrc object for probabilistic context likelihood of relatedness.
#
# Parameters:
# -----------
# num_sampling: int, number of subsampling procedures that select % of samples
#     to create partial networks. Defaults to 10000.
# frac_sampling: float, fraction of samples selected in each subsampling
#     procedure, should be between 0 and 1. Defaults to 0.75.
# q: float, top fraction of abosolute Pearson correlation coefficients (PCC)
#     which are considered as valid connectivity, should be between 0 and 1.
#     Defatults to 0.3, which indicates that top 30% absolute PCCs are accepted
#     so that corresponding pairs are set to be 1. and others are set to be 0.
#     If q=0., a hard threshold is set.
#     If 0. < q < 1., a threshold at the largest absolute PCC so that % of PCCs
#     larger than the threshold is set.
# corr_prob: float, probability threshold to select PCCs as valid connections
#     so that the PCCs are summed. Defaults to 0.9.
# alpha: float, significance level after permutation tests. Defaults to 0.05.
# bootstrap: bool, whether to use bootstrap for subsampling intead of random
#     subsampling. This is suitable when the number of samples is small.
#     Defaults to False.
# num_perms: int, number of permutations for permutation tests. Defaults to
#     10000.
# num_cores: int or None, number of cores for running the permutation tests
#     to speed up the calculations.
#
# Reference:
# ----------
#     [1] J. Proteome Res. 2015, 14, 1101–1111.
#     [2] J. Proteome Res. 2020, 19, 949−961.
corr_prob = 0.9
pclrc = PCLRC(num_sampling=int(1e4), bootstrap=True, num_perms=10000,
              corr_prob=corr_prob, num_cores=6)

In [19]:
# Calculates the connectivity for each metabolite based on the
# probabilities higher than the defined threshold, i.e., corr_prob
# for setting PCLRC object.
p = data_vals.shape[1]
var_conns = dict()
for g in pclrc.data_labels:
    # connectivity
    tmp_conns = np.zeros(p, dtype=np.float32)
    # probabilities
    tmp_probs = pclrc.pearson_corr_probs(label=g)
    for i in range(p):
        # group 1
        t_vx = tmp_probs[i] >= corr_prob
        if t_vx.any():
            tmp_conns[t_vx] += np.absolute(gp_pcc[g][i][t_vx])
    tmp_conns -= 1
    var_conns[g] = tmp_conns

plot connectivity¶

This section plots the connectivity between metabolites which have valid associations justified by PCLRC, that should have probabilities higher than predefine. A color map is used to indicate the connectivities. For the lines between metabolite pairs, only those having valid associations are shown, with width indidating the value of absolute PCC.
In [21]:
def plot_connectivity(pcc: np.ndarray,
                      conn_vals: np.ndarray,
                      probs: np.ndarray,
                      prob_thr: float,
                      max_conn: Optional[float] = None,
                      save_path: Optional[str] = None):
    """
    Plots the connectivities.

    Parameters:
    -----------
    pcc: Pearson correlation coefficients.
    conn_vals: Connectivities.
    probs: Association probabilities.
    prob_thr: Probability threshold.
    max_conn: Max connectivity for defining the color maps. This
        can be useful if both groups are plot so that colors in
        both plots are comparable.
        If this None, the max of current connectivity values, i.e,
        in `conn_vals` input is used.
    save_path: Full path to save the plot.

    """

    plt.close("all")

    # the radius of large circle
    rad_large = 15
    # the radius of small circle
    rad_small = 0.5
    # choose color map: here use Jet
    # https://matplotlib.org/stable/users/explain/colors/colormaps.html
    cmap = plt.get_cmap('OrRd')

    # angles of small circles on the large circle
    thetas = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, p, endpoint=False)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))

    # large circle
    ax.add_patch(plt.Circle((0, 0), rad_large, fc='none', ec='none'))

    # small circle center points
    metab_centers = [(rad_large * np.cos(theta), rad_large * np.sin(theta))
                     for theta in thetas]

    # plot the lines for connectivities, with the width of the lines indicating
    # the absolute PCC
    for i in range(p):
        ci_x, ci_y = metab_centers[i]
        for j in range(i + 1, p):
            if probs[i, j] > corr_prob:
                lw = abs(pcc[i, j]) ** 5 * 6
                cj_x, cj_y = metab_centers[j]
                ax.plot([ci_x, cj_x], [ci_y, cj_y], "gray", lw=lw,
                        alpha=0.5, zorder=1)

    # plot small circles with colors connectivities
    # map the values to colors in color maps
    vmax = conn_vals.max() if max_conn is None else max_conn
    cNorm = colors.Normalize(vmin=conn_vals.min(), vmax=vmax)
    scalarMap = cmx.ScalarMappable(norm=cNorm, cmap=cmap)
    for i, ck in enumerate(metab_centers):
        if conn_vals[i] > -1.:
            colorVal = scalarMap.to_rgba(conn_vals[i])
            ax.add_patch(
                plt.Circle(ck, rad_small, fc=colorVal, ec='none', zorder=10)
            )
        else:
            ax.add_patch(
                plt.Circle(ck, rad_small, fc="silver",
                           ec='none', zorder=10)
            )

    ax.autoscale_view()  # calculate the limits for the x and y axis
    ax.set_aspect('equal')  # show circles as circles

    # add color bar
    fig.colorbar(scalarMap, ax=ax, fraction=0.2, shrink=0.4, pad=0.,
                 orientation="horizontal", label=r"Connectivity")

    ax.tick_params(bottom=False, top=False, left=False, right=False,
                   labelbottom=False, labeltop=False, labelleft=False,
                   labelright=False)
    ax.spines[['right', 'top', "bottom", "left"]].set_visible(False)

    plt.tight_layout()

    if save_path is not None:
        plt.savefig(save_path, dpi=1200, bbox_inches='tight')

    plt.show()

# plots the connectivity for each group to show the results
plt.close("all")

# remove those metabolites having differences in connectivity of 0
jx = d_chis != 0.
nv = np.count_nonzero(jx)
# valid p values
pvals2 = pvals[jx]

# p value threshold after BH correction at predefined FDR
pthr = sig_pvals[-1]

# -log10(p)
lpx = -np.log10(pvals2)

xx = np.arange(nv)

# get color map
cmap = plt.get_cmap('OrRd')
cNorm = colors.Normalize(vmin=lpx.min(), vmax=lpx.max())
scalarMap = cmx.ScalarMappable(norm=cNorm, cmap=cmap)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))
bars = ax.bar(xx, d_chis[jx], zorder=10)
ax.plot([-1., p], [0, 0], "k", lw=0.6)

ax.grid(axis="x", zorder=0, ls=":")
ax.set_xticks(xx, labels=metabs[jx], rotation=90, ha="center", fontsize=10)

# set colors of bars and tick labels
xt_lbs = ax.get_xticklabels()
tc = scalarMap.to_rgba(lpx.max())
for i, (xlb, b) in enumerate(zip(xt_lbs, bars)):
    if pvals2[i] <= pthr:
        # this is significant
        b.set_color(scalarMap.to_rgba(lpx[i]))
        xlb.set_color(tc)
        xlb.set_fontweight("bold")
    else:
        # this is not significant
        b.set_color("silver")
        xlb.set_color("dimgray")

ax.set_xlim(left=-1., right=nv)

ax.set_ylabel("Difference in connectivity", fontsize=16)

fig.colorbar(scalarMap, ax=ax, fraction=0.2, shrink=0.4, pad=0.02,
             location='top', orientation="horizontal", label=r"-$log_{10}$(p)")

plt.tight_layout()

# save the figure to "some path"
# plt.savefig(r"some path/figure_name.png", dpi=1200,
#             bbox_inches='tight')

plt.show()
